Hands down the quickest way to cook a whole chicken! Whole birds used to be so intimidating to me. Now they’re so quick and easy to prepare!

Start with your trivet in the instant pot… this is important. I forgot the trivet once and it ended badly.
Add the chicken + 1 cup water for the IP to reach pressure.
Put a little olive oil on the chicken, season however you like, I added some chopped onions.
High pressure for 32 minutes. Fall off the bone tender chicken!

** YES I’ve used a frozen chicken. Do 40 minutes instead of 32.**

I like to save the juice from the IP and use it to start chicken noodle soup with the leftover chicken! So good.

#easymeals #instantpot #quickmeals #frommykitchen #recipes #easyrecipes #farmfood

Ever heard of a CCI meter? It measures Chlorophyll Concentration Index.  I hadn’t heard of it either.

Long story short, this meter allows us to measure chlorophyll concentration, real time, in plants.  Then we can calculate now much nitrogen the plant has at that very moment.

We care about this because it gave us insight into whether the @pivotbio PROVEN40 we applied was working throughout the growing season.  Spoiler alert: it was working WELL. 

Swipe to see some plant comparisons throughout the growing season and then read more about it on the blog.  Check out the YouTube video to see this magic meter in action!

#pivotbiopartner and proud of it!

To be completely honest, 2022 has been my hardest year in a lot of ways. I wasn’t even sure what to say to sum up the year. But looking back through my camera roll and reminiscing on these moments I found myself smiling a lot more than anything else. This year was hard but seeing all the GOOD that happened this year made me realize how truly blessed I am AND how much my perspective can shift when I focus on the good.

So that’s my goal for 2023, to focus on the good. To feel the hard things when they come and work through them, but then to focus on what’s really good and what serves me well.

We farmed, we had fun, we laughed, we cried. We saw a LOT of change come our way. I stepped back from my career, we joined a TV show, we shipped beef to all 50 states, we survived the most destructive growing season we’ve ever had, we were blessed with another healthy pregnancy, and we spent much more intentional time with our boys.

I’m ready for the 2022 chapter to close and I am so excited to welcome in 2023. Here’s to wishing you all a very happy and SAFE new year!

Catch ya on the flip side 🥳🥰

Pretty much the only way we make baked potatoes these days. It’s quick and consistent and the potatoes are tender and moist EVERY time. 🥔😍

Instant Pot Baked Potatoes:
Put potatoes on trivet in instant pot. Add 1 cup water. High pressure for 20 minutes. That’s it. That is literally it. You can quick release or natural release, both work well. Don’t overthink it.

Also shout out to @feedlotsofpeople for teaching me that the lid fits in the handle 😱 total life saver. And I owned an IP for an embarrassing amount of time before I learned this. Let me know if you just now learned it too!

Hog Butcher 2023 by the numbers.

What started as a basic act of survival back in 1885 when Levi’s family first immigrated here from Germany has turned into a long standing, multi generational family tradition.

A few years ago we were butchering 6 hogs in a weekend, then 8, then 11, and now 14! As our family grows and our friends grow more interested in being a part of putting meat on their family’s tables, the hog butcher tradition has grown too. It’s not just about knowing where your food comes from, it’s about preserving some of the most important life skills and ensuring the next generation will be able to feed themselves, no matter what.

I wish I had an actual recipe for you but I literally just wing most soups with whatever is in my fridge. This is the gist of what I do! Forgot to show seasonings in this but I usually just season to taste with Nature’s and Celery Salt. 

Here’s a list of what I usually use. As with most everything I make…. I measure with my heart 🫶🏼

• 4ish cups shredded chicken 
• 1 bag frozen egg noodles 
• carrots, celery, and an onion chopped (use the food processor #easy)
• for the broth I usually use the juices left over after cooking a whole chicken in the instant pot, then I add water and more homemade chicken broth OR use Better than Bouillon to make some nice flavorful broth to add
• season to taste using Nature’s and celery salt or whatever your favorite seasonings are

** there’s no true order this has to be in. I’ve been in a hurry before and just dumped it all together, brought it to a boil, then let it simmer for a few hours or until we’re ready to eat!

It’s simple, don’t overthink it. You can do it!!

Cream of literally AnYtHinG Soup! I always have this stuff on hand so when I’m throwing a casserole together or anything that calls for cream soup I just whip this up with what’s in my fridge. I’ve used mushrooms, carrots, celery, onion, chicken broth, and sometimes a combination of all of the above. You can’t mess this up. It’s easy!

Credit for this trick goes to my mother in law. She told me how to do this shortly after Levi and I got married but I resisted doing it for SO LONG because canned soup just seemed so much simpler. Well, the older I get the more I care about simple ingredients and the more I appreciate homemade versions of processed foods. SO I am now a homemade cream soup believer and am happy to share the super simple recipe with y’all!

Cream (of literally anything) soup:
• Chop up whatever veggies are in your fridge that you want to turn into a cream soup. (Mushrooms, celery, carrots, etc) I’ve also used chicken broth as the base to make cream of chicken!
• Sauté in butter and season with whatever you’d like! We love Nature’s!
• Once the veggies are soft, turn the heat off to let them cool a little bit. 
• Mix 1 cup cold milk with 1 heaping Tbsp corn starch. Mix really well until allllll the clumps are gone! Someone told me you could shake it in a shaker bottle too!
• Once the veggies have cooled a little, add the milk/cornstarch mix to the pan and start stirring over medium heat. If you add the milk to a hot pan it can curdle! It only happened once before I learned to cool it off a little.
• Stir constantly over medium heat until the milk thickens making a nice creamy soup!
• Add to whatever recipe that calls for a cream soup! 

** The 1 cup milk to 1 Tbsp cornstarch is roughly equal to one can of cream soup.

Save this for later and let me know if you try it!!

#homemade #easyrecipes #cleanrecipes #cleaneating #simplemeals

Levi always jokes that a good rancher never knows **exactly** how many cows he has. “He can get ya close though”

These actually aren’t our cows. But we did care for them for a good portion of the winter. We live right in the middle of crop country. If you fly over our county it’s miles and miles of that perfectly quilted looking landscape, squares upon squares of fields.

Our climate allows for one growing season per year. After our crops are harvested, there’s a lot of roughage, organic matter, and grain that fell before reaching the combine left behind. All of this left behind in the field is GREAT feed for cattle.

We live in the land of corn fields, these cows come from the Sandhills aka the land of rolling pastures. Western Nebraska and surrounding states have been in a major drought. Droughts so bad that rancher’s hay crops are half of what they usually get and half of what they need to feed their cows all winter. That’s where these miles and miles of corn stalks come in. Ranchers send their cows to farmers like us to watch on our cornstalks through the winter months. It’s great feed for these cows and it’s great for the farmer because the cows poop all over our fields (think free fertilizer), the cows break up compacted areas with their hooves, and the cows clean up that grain that the combine missed which cuts down on volunteer plants the next growing season.

It’s a win win for both the farmer and the rancher.

#cowsitting #cornstalks #customgrazing #customfarming #cattlecountry #cows #cattle #rancher #farmer

The auto sensing wipers are all fun and games until it starts to sprinkle when your steaks are thawing on the windshield. 😅

You’d think stuff like this would eventually stop surprising me 🤣

Wildshield Steaks: The Saga

Here’s the whole story: we were headed to lake and in true Ochsner fashion we ended up leaving 3 hours later than originally planned #farmlife. We forgot to thaw our steaks during the day so they were frozen solid when we finally left and remembered to grab them! We had a 2 hour drive and would arrive at supper time when the steaks needed to go on the grill. We tried leaving them inside the car on the dash, but Levi felt like they weren’t thawing at all so had then genius idea to put them on the windshield under the wipers so “warm air would blow on them” 😅

It was touch and go and we almost lost them TWICE when we drove through VERY light rain that made the auto sensing wipers start. Thankfully, our supper was spared and we made it to our destination with thawed ribeyes 🥩😎

So, yes, we are fully aware of more conventional ways to thaw our meat. We were just in a pinch so Levi improvised!

#cantmakethisup #steaks #beefitswhatsfordinner

It’s BEEF MONTH.

It takes a village to raise great quality beef for our safe food supply. #ad 

It starts during calving season when we’re out of town at a conference or snuck away for a date night and our family or neighbors take a night check for us.  As the calves grow and the grass greens, the herd gets hauled to summer pasture.  Since we can’t lay eyes on our pasture every day, the neighbors down there give us a call if a fence is down or a cow gets out.  Harvest rolls around and it’s time to start fencing off fields to bring in cows in on our cornstalks.  Truckers haul cattle from several hundred miles away to graze stalks during the winter.  Our own herd gets brought home to our corn stalks as well.  Neighbors and friends gather many times to help with cattle drives as cows move from field to field to graze fresh stalks. Winter comes with it’s own set of challenges and sometimes a cow or calf gets sick.  Local vets help us decide a treatment plan to get the animals back on track.

This beef month we are celebrating the community of fellow producers and ag companies that help make raising great beef a reality! Thanks @zoetiscattle for being a part of our village!

Learned what tillers are this growing season - they’re pretty cool and they make my farmer V happy.

Tillers: lateral branches that shoot up from the main corn stalk that signify favorable growing conditions. They could also shoot up following damage to the stalks, but in this case it’s because the crop is thriving. 

Basically, the corn plants are getting all the nutrients they need.  A big part of our fertility program is the PROVEN40 product from @pivotbio.  We’re applying microbes to our soil that create nitrogen all season long, just as the corn is needing it.

Just when I thought I found a topic my husband couldn’t refer to food while talking about…. He call’s the FurrowJet from @precision.planting “the buffet” for corn.

Here’s what he means: the FurrowJet allows us to apply fertilizer in furrow (while we plant) to THREE different zones (one on top of the seed plus the root zone to the side of each seed). These three zones create the fertilizer buffet for the corn seeds.  Traditional in furrow applicators apply in just one zone, more of a fast food joint as opposed to a fancy buffet.  We use the FurrowJet to apply microbes to the seed zone and starter fertilizer to the zones on each side. 

#precisionplantingpartner

Stop. At. The. Corners.

Do I need to hash this out again? It’s farm safety week so I’ll go ahead and hash away…
 
I know what you’re thinking… fields are being harvested so you think it’s safe to drive through those corners on gravel roads to save some time…  WRONGO!

STOP 🛑🌽

If you hang onto anything from me I pray it’s this... when the corn is tall, STOP at the corners.

Even if you don’t have a stop sign... STOP at the corners.

Even if you know the other direction has a stop sign... STOP at the corners.

I don’t care if you’re walking, riding a bike, driving an ATV, driving a vehicle, or any piece of farm equipment... STOP at the corners.

Corn is TALL and it blocks all visibility at intersections. Watching for dust flying up during the day or headlights when it is dark just isn’t enough... STOP at the corners.

NEVER trust that whoever might be driving from the other direction will stop. TOO many people have been hurt or killed in accidents at blind corners during the peak of growing season. Levi’s aunt almost died when she was a little girl because someone RAN a STOP sign during growing season! That’s why I say don’t trust that other vehicles will stop!! Just pleeease always STOP until every last field is harvested!

Life is precious and being in a hurry just isn’t worth it y’all.. take the extra time and always AWAYS stop at the corners.

It’s farm safety week, so let’s make our best effort to spread the word!

Tell your friends!

#harvest2023
#farmsafety #farmsafetyweek #stopatthecorners

For whatever reason I always told my self that fruit crisps and cobblers were intimidating. If you’re of this same mindset, let me change your mind!

I stopped in to see Levi’s grandma when we were harvesting their corn and she sent me on my way with a 5gal bucket of fresh picked apples. I made apple sauce and still had some apples so tried an apple crisp for the first time. Per usual, I changed the recipe, measured with my heart, and sprinkled some extras on top! It was farmer approved and the actually asked me to make three times in less than 2 weeks 😍 Here’s what I came up with:

Caramely Apple Crisp 🍎 

Apples sliced and cored to fill 9x13 pan (idk how many I had little apples and used 15 maybe?) 
1 cup sugar 
1 T flour
1 to 2 tsp cinnamon 
*toss dry ingredients to coat apples in pan 

Topping:
2 cup brown sugar
1 cup butter melted 
1 1/2 cup oats
1 cup flour 
(Salt, nutmeg, and cinnamon to sprinkle)

Melt butter, add brown sugar, oats, and flour. Spread over top of apples. Sprinkle salt, nutmeg, and cinnamon on top. Bake at 350 for 1 hour. 🍎

Save it for later and let me know if you try it! 🤩

Beck’s. These four things were my biggest takeaways from touring the @beckshybrids headquarters.

Legacy - a true family run, faith based operation. The family history is well documented and was very cool to experience! The strong values @beckshybrids has built their business on are leaving an incredible legacy. 

Hospitality - I’ve never felt so welcomed by complete strangers! They picked us up at our most local airport flew us on their beautiful falcon aircraft to tour the facility, fed us a great lunch, and flew us back home safely. A once in a lifetime experience I won’t soon forget!

Transparency - they showed us EVERYTHING! There were no secrets and no parts of the processing facilities they didn’t open the doors for us to see. From the germ lab and green houses to the processing floor and high yield research plat - we saw it ALL and ALL of our questions were answered! 

Innovation - did I mention they have ten greenhouses and are planting and harvesting research hybrids every day of the year? And a high yield research plot aimed at not only growing high yield corn, but doing so to find the limiting factors so farmers can continually improve. 

I could say SO much more about our day with the Beck’s family, but I’ll leave you with this: there’s a lot of noise in today’s world and spending the day with a company truly built on a solid faith foundation was the biggest breath of fresh air!

Cows grazing cornstalks just makes sense.  It’s a partnership between farmers and ranchers that was born of necessity, innovation, and diversity. #sponsored 

Necessity - ranchers in drought stricken areas needed a winter feed option and our fields needed cleaned up to cut down on volunteer corn the following growing season. 

Innovation - the cows poop all over our fields (yay natural fertilizer!) and their hooves help break up hard pieces of soil. 

Diversity - the rancher diversifies his winter feeding and the farmer diversifies his income during the off season. 

We are farmers and ranchers linking arms to get through every season.  We are born of tenacity, the long haul, the tough grind to get through the trying times.  We are born of camaraderie, community, and unconditional support.  We are born of innovation.  We are born of the bond. 

Thank you @zoetiscattle for always rooting for the cattle producer and helping tell the unique stories of farmers and ranchers like us! 

#BornOfTheBond
